H - History
The 1918 flu pandemic, also known as the Spanish flu, was an unusually deadly influenza pandemic caused by the H1N1 influenza A virus. Lasting from February 1918 to April 1920, it infected 500 million people–about a third of the world's population at the time–in four successive waves.

node.text: Today I rediscovered this picture of my grandfather behind the pulpit at Richlands Tabernacle in August of 1955. The campmeeting has been held the first full week of August for more than 8 decades until this year. The pandemic has interrupted all of our lives so much. Thankfully the God that always met with us every year at campmeeting is unchanging. Nothing can interrupt the love God has for us. Not even COVID-19 can separate us from Him. Nothing can separate us from God’s love. Romans 8:31-39 #meetingattheoldcampground #richlandstabernaclecampmeeting #richlandstabernacle  #godisalwaysthere #hewillneverleaveme #covid19 #pandemic2020 #lifeinterrupted
